      <hedline>
        <hl1>Shopping, Your Way</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Chris Morrow letter comments on Sept 14 Online Shopping column on maintaining anonymity while shopping online</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I read with interest the Online Shopping column about undercover buying.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I read with interest the Online Shopping column about undercover buying.</p>
        <p>Sounds like a hassle. What I found amazing, and a little depressing, was that Michelle Slatalla spent time trying to be anonymous on Amazon.com but didn't consider going to a site that valued her privacy.</p>
        <p>If Amazon's new privacy policy bothers her -- which it should -- she could go to any of the thousands of independent bookstores around the country that will never sell their customers' information to anyone, period. Try going to www.booksense.com to find some of them, or visit my store's site, www.northshire.com.</p>
        <p>CHRIS MORROW  Manchester Center, Vt.</p>
        <p>The writer is general manager of the Northshire Bookstore.</p>
      </block>
